## What happened

Apple's cryptographic frameworks (Security.framework / CommonCrypto) **dropped DSA support**. .NET on macOS delegates to the OS crypto libraries, so once Apple removed it, `DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS. Earlier .NET versions either shipped with an OpenSSL-based fallback or Apple hadn't yet removed the API surface — .NET 11 no longer papers over it.

## How to fix it

**Option A — Migrate away from DSA (recommended):**
DSA is considered legacy. Re-sign with **ECDSA** or **Ed25519**, which are supported on all three platforms.

**Option B — Use a managed/cross-platform DSA implementation:**
If you must verify existing DSA signatures you can't re-sign, use **BouncyCastle** (`Portable.BouncyCastle` or `BouncyCastle.Cryptography` on NuGet):

```csharp
// Instead of DSA.Create()
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
verifier.Init(forSigning: false, publicKeyParam);
verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
```

**Option C — Install OpenSSL on macOS and P/Invoke to it:**
`brew install openssl`, then point your code at `libssl` via `[DllImport]` — but this adds a deployment dependency and is fragile.

### TL;DR
Apple removed DSA → .NET 11 on macOS can't provide it. Use **BouncyCastle** for legacy signature verification, and plan a migration to **ECDSA/Ed25519**.
